article.headline: Golden State 92, Phoenix 83
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Golden State Warriors are now .500 thanks to defense and rebounding. Jason Richardson had 25 points and 13 rebounds to lead Golden State past the Phoenix Suns 92-83 Friday night, the Warriors' season-best third straight win. It was the first win in five road games for Golden State, which improved to 7-7. "The key was the rebounding and defensive focus," coach Eric Musselman said after the Warriors outrebounded the Suns 50-33. "We overcame our poor free throw shooting and 3-point shooting to win a big game." The Warriors' defensive plan was to try and stop Stephon Marbury, the Suns' leading scorer and playmaker. They succeeded. Marbury, who was averaging 19.1 points and 8.6 assists per game, scored only 14 points on 5-of-16 shooting, and had six assists, ending his run of five consecutive double-doubles. Speedy Claxton was entrusted with the job of guarding Marbury and he shadowed him constantly. "I wanted to make him take tough shots with a hand in his face," Claxton said. "I wanted to force him a certain way and the big men would be there (if he got past him). I wanted to give him only one angle instead of letting him choose." The loss ended Phoenix's four-game home winning streak. Before Friday, the Suns had a 70-22 record against the Warriors at home, including 15 wins in the previous 16 games. The sharp-shooting Richardson, the Warriors' leading scorer this season and the NBA's leading rebounder among guards, hit 12-of-21 shots but downplayed his performance. "I got a lot of opportunities because (center Erick) Dampier didn't play a lot," Richardson said. Dampier, the NBA's leading rebounder, played only 28 minutes, but had 11 rebounds and 11 points. Mike Dunleavy added 16 points for the Warriors, and Nick Van Exel and Claxton had 12 apiece. Reserve Penny Hardaway led the Suns with 16 points. Casey Jacobsen, making his first NBA start, scored 14, including four 3-pointers. Golden State took a 19-4 lead in the first seven minutes as the Suns missed 12 of their first 13 shots and never trailed the rest of the game. Richardson scored 16 points in the first half -- five more than the entire Phoenix starting five. After the Suns closed the deficit to four points, 32-28, early in the second period, the Warriors went on another run, outscoring Phoenix 17-7 during the rest of the quarter and led 49-35 at halftime. The Suns' first-half total was their lowest of the season. The Suns' starters -- Jacobsen, Amare Stoudemire, Jahidi White, Marbury and Joe Johnson -- were 4-for-22 in the first half. The poor shooting came after the Suns had shot 54.4 percent and scored 121 points, both season highs, in their previous game. "We dug ourselves too deep of a hole, and against a team like that ... they're good," Jacobsen said. "It was an uphill struggle the rest of the way and we couldn't get it done."

Game notes
The Suns also are 1-4 away from home, with their lone win away from America West Arena at Golden State. ... Rookie forward Zarko Cabarpaka, who is expected to be sidelined 6-to-8 weeks with a broken right wrist, was placed on the injured list by the Suns, who activated 6-foot-11 forward Robert Archibald. ... Golden State has already used four different starting lineups in 14 games, with no combination being used more than five times. Last season, the Warriors used only two starting lineups. ... Shawn Marion, the Suns' third-leading scorer (15.5), missed his second straight game because of a sprained left ankle. ... The Warriors have 16 players on their roster, one over the NBA limit of 15. Because of injuries or suspensions, seven Warriors have missed significant playing time already, and the NBA has granted the team two hardship exemptions, allowing Golden State to add additional players to the active roster.
